# Development Preferences

## Scope and focus

- Focus on the areas of code relevant to the task
- Only make changes that are requested or that you are confident are well understood and related to the request
- Do not touch code that is unrelated to the task
- Before changing code, consider what other methods and areas might be affected

## Simplicity and consistency

- Prefer simple solutions
- Avoid duplication — check for existing code and functionality before adding new logic
- When fixing a bug, exhaust options within the current implementation before introducing a new pattern or technology
- If you must replace an approach, remove the old implementation so logic is not duplicated
- Avoid major changes to patterns and architecture once a feature works well, unless explicitly instructed
- Keep the codebase clean and organized
- Refactor when a file grows beyond roughly 200–300 lines

## Environments and data

- Write code that accounts for dev, test, and prod environments
- Mock data belongs in tests only — never in dev or prod code paths
- Never add stubbing or fake data patterns that affect dev or prod behaviour
- **Never overwrite `.env` files without asking and confirming first**

## Testing and scripts

- Write thorough tests for all major functionality
- Avoid one-off scripts committed to the repo when a command or existing tooling suffices

## Protected areas

- **Never overwrite shared primitive or vendor UI components without explicit instruction** (e.g. generated or third-party building blocks)
